            <lb/>
2&#xD;<lb/>
Which only Meant the breath which <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">spiro</add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">was</del> supposed&#xD;<lb/>
to be the vital principle&#xD;<lb/>
The thinking Powers depend&#xD;<lb/>
On Organisation &#xD;<lb/>
– or –&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
15&#xD;<lb/>
2&#xD;<lb/>
The Body organised Matter.&#xD;<lb/>
The Immortality of the Soul is an established&#xD;<lb/>
Theory &amp; is generally believed in the Christian&#xD;<lb/>
World &amp; such is the blind Credulity of the&#xD;<lb/>
Generality of Mankind that hating&#xD;<lb/>
the investigation of Truth, They do not scruple&#xD;<lb/>
to reprobate the Man who makes any attempts&#xD;<lb/>
towards it.&#xD;<lb/>
Many of our learned divines have attempted to prove&#xD;<lb/>
But alass their endeavours have been &#xD;<lb/>
vain &amp; futile&#xD;<lb/>
the immateriality of the Soul. Many of our&#xD;<lb/>
Philosophers have beleived &amp; attempted to prove it&#xD;<lb/>
but all their <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxxx xxxx xx</unclear> vain</del> Attempts have miscarried&#xD;<lb/>
Many after long dissertations have sat down&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; asserted that it was a truth beyond human&#xD;<lb/>
Comprehension &amp; to be proved from the holy&#xD;<lb/>
Scriptures alone.&#xD;<lb/>
In the Scriptures we find nothing of it except&#xD;<lb/>
some few hints in the new Testament which&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
16&#xD;<lb/>
are far from amounting to a demonstration –&#xD;<lb/>
Now if Writers of the old testament were materialists&#xD;<lb/>
And those of the new, immaterialists, &amp; both inspired&#xD;<lb/>
Writers. The ballance is equal. &amp; both Sects&#xD;<lb/>
may defend their Doctrines from the scriptures&#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">But as such proofs on either side must be equivocal</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <del rend="strikethrough">Reason &amp; the light of the nature are the</del> evidences</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which we ought to follow;</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Prejudice shoud never lead us to believe Theories</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Which are absurd &amp; contrary to common Sense.</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The body is a fine tuned Machine. The nerves</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">are those parts which convey Sensation to the brain <add>the place where sensation dwells</add>
            </del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The Passions depend on the tune of the nervous</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">System. Those whose nerves are finely formed</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp; harmoniously disposed have fine feelings &amp;</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Passions. This is what we call susceptibility</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which is often supposed to be an attribute of the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Soul. A Man in a Lethargy loses their</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">susceptibility when the Generality of the nerves</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
17&#xD;<lb/>
If the Soul was distinct from Body&#xD;<lb/>
are primarily affected.&#xD;<lb/>
its Connexion with body might influence it but coud nevr destroy it&#xD;<lb/>
A Man in a Mania often loses all recollection&#xD;<lb/>
in an Apoplexy the use of all his senses.&#xD;<lb/>
This proves the brain to be the grand stamen&#xD;<lb/>
of all the Mental faculties. when the brain is&#xD;<lb/>
materialy injured, Stupidity loss of Memory &amp;&#xD;<lb/>
Apathy are the Consequences.&#xD;<lb/>
as&#xD;<lb/>
If Memory, Recollection &amp; aptness to receive impression&#xD;<lb/>
or ideas are the faculties of the brain, Sensation&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Susceptibility the attributes of the nerves.&#xD;<lb/>
What Powers can we give the Soul?&#xD;<lb/>
Is it the bare vivifying Principle which gives <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Perception &amp;</add> volition?&#xD;<lb/>
You will answer no. for Snails possess this in&#xD;<lb/>
the same degree as Men. then this results&#xD;<lb/>
from the Machinism of the body, I beleive&#xD;<lb/>
no one ever gave immaterial Souls, to snails.&#xD;<lb/>
Sensation they allow is the faculty of the nerves.&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="20"
                xml:id="pb-20"
                facs="#i20"/>
            <lb/>
18&#xD;<lb/>
Is a thing then which really exists so hard to be&#xD;<lb/>
defined? They universally pretend that it is&#xD;<lb/>
the power of thinking, an immaterial simple&#xD;<lb/>
essence endowed with modes &amp; faculties. –&#xD;<lb/>
Powers never exist abstract from Substance&#xD;<lb/>
Powers themselves are modes.&#xD;<lb/>
Allow Perception to be a mode of body resulting&#xD;<lb/>
from organization. The lowest <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">works</del> <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ranks</add> of animate beings&#xD;<lb/>
possess it <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in the same degree</del> as man.&#xD;<lb/>
Allow Memory to be an attribute of the brain&#xD;<lb/>
Reflection depends on memory.&#xD;<lb/>
The Power of Thinking is but a Combination&#xD;<lb/>
of the other faculties of the Mind, can it&#xD;<lb/>
exist abstract from sensation perception&#xD;<lb/>
The Soul as liable to no change coud nevr be affected&#xD;<lb/>
by bodily&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Memory? Whatever is liable to no change can never receive&#xD;<lb/>
Impressions –&#xD;<lb/>
There are faculties resulting from organisation&#xD;<lb/>
Consequently thinking &amp;c depend on Organisation&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="21"
                xml:id="pb-21"
                facs="#i21"/>
            <lb/>
19&#xD;<lb/>
At the time that you deprive Man of these&#xD;<lb/>
faculties you deprive him of the power of thinking.&#xD;<lb/>
Many Men exist without thinking for hours&#xD;<lb/>
when in a sound Sleep –&#xD;<lb/>
Where are the powers of thinking Perception&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Recollection, in a swoon. are they annihilated&#xD;<lb/>
for a short space &amp; again created anew?&#xD;<lb/>
No they are suspended say the immaterialists&#xD;<lb/>
An immaterial unchangeable <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xx</unclear>
            </del>
            <lb/>
being cannot have any of its powers <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">diminished</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">diminished</add>
            <lb/>
or extended this destroys their Argument.&#xD;<lb/>
Many Men have been for hours under Water have&#xD;<lb/>
had every faculty of the Mind suspended &amp; almost&#xD;<lb/>
all the vital motions at a stop; Yet have <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">been</del>
            <lb/>
recovered but they coud give no account of&#xD;<lb/>
the intermediate state. where was the Soul&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="22"
                xml:id="pb-22"
                facs="#i22"/>
            <lb/>
20&#xD;<lb/>
at that Period? no one can a<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">n</add>swer it was not.&#xD;<lb/>
There was no memory &amp; no perception. &amp; consequently&#xD;<lb/>
no thought.&#xD;<lb/>
This proves Thinking to be effect of organization&#xD;<lb/>
The Immaterialists have maintained an impious&#xD;<lb/>
Opinion. that that God one of whose attributes&#xD;<lb/>
they assert to be Omnipotence cannot make&#xD;<lb/>
Matter think. They judge of his faculties&#xD;<lb/>
by their own &amp; think because they are not&#xD;<lb/>
capable of organising <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">matter</del> &amp; animating <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>x</unclear>
            </del>
            <lb/>
Matter that the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#misc_511"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag3">
          Supreme being
        </term>
            </rs> whose <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">suppose</add> will&#xD;<lb/>
the Elements obey is alike incapable.&#xD;<lb/>
Nor do they scruple to call that Man&#xD;<lb/>
an Heretic who in the least attempts&#xD;<lb/>
to invade their opinions&#xD;<lb/>
Man cannot pretend to judge of the&#xD;<lb/>
powers of nature.&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="23"
                xml:id="pb-23"
                facs="#i23"/>
            <lb/>
21&#xD;<lb/>
Perhaps If we were to trace the Doctrine of&#xD;<lb/>
the Immortality of the Soul to its true origin&#xD;<lb/>
We shall find that it was born in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag4" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
amongst the Crafty Priests who that they&#xD;<lb/>
might make men more subservient to&#xD;<lb/>
their ends asserted. that the soul or thinking&#xD;<lb/>
Power, were immortal (whereas they might&#xD;<lb/>
as well have <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">asserted</add> colour or motion to be eternal&#xD;<lb/>
after the Dissolution of the bodies to which&#xD;<lb/>
they belonged) <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp; that tho</del>se who erred&#xD;<lb/>
against their God or resisted their&#xD;<lb/>
views shoud be punished in a future&#xD;<lb/>
state. &amp; vice versa.&#xD;<lb/>
This Doctrine was transported by&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag5" type="person">
          Pythagoras
        </name>
            </rs> to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#place_167"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="place">
          Greece
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="24"
                xml:id="pb-24"
                facs="#i24"/>
            <lb/>
22&#xD;<lb/>
The first Philosophers beleived that the soul&#xD;<lb/>
was composed of the several Elements.&#xD;<lb/>
some supposed it air others water &amp;c <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">xxxx</unclear>
            <lb/>
But the Enlightened Moderns knowing that&#xD;<lb/>
if they allowed the Soul to be material&#xD;<lb/>
their Systems woud be quickly overturned&#xD;<lb/>
Asserted its immateriality tho’ at the&#xD;<lb/>
same time they asserted its incomprehensibility&#xD;<lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
One of the greatest argument for Materialism is&#xD;<lb/>
that a Child has no reasoning but performs&#xD;<lb/>
all its offices by what they call instinct&#xD;<lb/>
namely when the calls of hunger invite it&#xD;<lb/>
to eat it seeks no other food except&#xD;<lb/>
the Milk of its Mother. &amp; takes the teat&#xD;<lb/>
as the beasts indeed it does not at all&#xD;<lb/>
differ from them only as being a more helpless&#xD;<lb/>
animal –&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="25"
                xml:id="pb-25"
                facs="#i25"/>
            <lb/>
23&#xD;<lb/>
3.&#xD;<lb/>
On Governments.&#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The Most Perfect form of government is that in</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which, the People form their own laws &amp; govern</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">themselves. This is called a republic<del rend="strikethrough">an form</del>
            </del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <del rend="strikethrough">
                  <unclear>x</unclear>
               </del> Europe has beheld the formation of many</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">petty Republicks within her territories. Most of</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which have been formed &amp; governed with Success</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The largest of these did not contain above 3 Millions</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of Subjects. -</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">We have in these last Centuries beheld <del rend="strikethrough">
                  <unclear>x</unclear>
               </del> a mighty</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Nation groning under the Chains of Tyranny &amp; sustaining</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the pangs of Oppression nobly break the yoke.</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">We have beheld her form of a Government approaching</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The nearest to Perfection.</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="26"
                xml:id="pb-26"
                facs="#i26"/>
            <lb/>
24 &#xD;<lb/>
– On the Credulity of Mortals –&#xD;<lb/>
Credulity &amp; prejudice have been the grand obstacles&#xD;<lb/>
to the investigation of truth in all ages.&#xD;<lb/>
Those Men <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">of form <del rend="strikethrough">
                  <unclear>xx xxxx</unclear>
               </del>
            </add> whose soundness of Head &amp; purity&#xD;<lb/>
of Heart enabled them to make researches&#xD;<lb/>
into those things which Ignorance had instituted&#xD;<lb/>
Prejudice continued &amp; Credulity beliveded&#xD;<lb/>
were looked on with Horror. <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xx</unclear>
            </del> stigmatized&#xD;<lb/>
with the Names of Infidels &amp; Heretics; persecuted&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; even <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">suffered Martyrdom</del>. &amp; even sacrificed&#xD;<lb/>
at the Altars of the Gods.&#xD;<lb/>
Men by an unhappy fatality seem to be&#xD;<lb/>
blind to Dictates of Reason &amp; He who might&#xD;<lb/>
if He properly employed his faculties <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>woud</unclear>
            </del>
            <lb/>
be a dignified &amp; noble animal in the scale&#xD;<lb/>
of Creation, becomes by the errors of opinion&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="27"
                xml:id="pb-27"
                facs="#i27"/>
            <lb/>
25&#xD;<lb/>
The government of Prejudice &amp; the Doctrines of&#xD;<lb/>
Credulity a mean &amp; despicable Creature.&#xD;<lb/>
Blind &amp; yet Presumptuous ignorant yet arrogant&#xD;<lb/>
Guilty of mean actions yet proud of Committing&#xD;<lb/>
them.&#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Most of the Errors in Government &amp; religion arise</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">from two sources Prejudice &amp; credulity.</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">If you sift the hearts or ask the opinions of the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Generality of Mankind you will find this</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to be true. if you inquire of many why</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">they prefer this form to that, they answer</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The Common <del rend="strikethrough">Errors</del> of Mankind</del>
            <lb/>
Happy was that State of Man when all men&#xD;<lb/>
were equal in knowledge when all were alike&#xD;<lb/>
ignorant. Priestcraft was then unknown&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="28"
                xml:id="pb-28"
                facs="#i28"/>
            <lb/>
26&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Men obey’d that simple Religion which nature&#xD;<lb/>
gave them. there was then no war for there&#xD;<lb/>
was nothing to contend for there was then&#xD;<lb/>
no sacrifices <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <rs xml:id="ttag7" ref="#nonenglish_057" type="nonenglish">
                  <term xml:id="tag7">
          cest a dire. des hommes
        </term>
               </rs>
            </add> at the altars of the Gods for&#xD;<lb/>
all man believed the same Religion.&#xD;<lb/>
The unequal Distribution of Knowledge &amp; the ignorant&#xD;<lb/>
prejudices &amp; credulity of Men have caused&#xD;<lb/>
all the Evils which have since happened to&#xD;<lb/>
the Human <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Race</add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Nature by Chance gave one</del> man &#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">more mental &amp; Corporeal powers than another</del>
            <lb/>
The first Governments were instituted for the&#xD;<lb/>
General Safety of all. &amp; power was placed&#xD;<lb/>
in the hands of the best &amp; wisest&#xD;<lb/>
Since that alass the blindness of Mortals&#xD;<lb/>
have Mistaken Hypocrisy for Religion&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Craft for wisdom. Prejudice &amp; credulity&#xD;<lb/>
have Confirmed the errors which blindness causes&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="29"
                xml:id="pb-29"
                facs="#i29"/>
            <lb/>
27&#xD;<lb/>
Men Glory in the Chains which Tyranny has imposed&#xD;<lb/>
upon them &amp; prefer Slavery to freedom &amp; absurdity&#xD;<lb/>
to truth. Alass how long will the human Mind&#xD;<lb/>
Continue in bondage. how long e’er it <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">will</add> casts&#xD;<lb/>
of the Fetters of Prejudice &amp; exert its proper&#xD;<lb/>
faculties? Till that time Man will be&#xD;<lb/>
a despicable Animal. A few in all ages&#xD;<lb/>
have risen up &amp; preached those Doctrines which&#xD;<lb/>
Reason assents to. but how I shudder when I&#xD;<lb/>
read the treatment the experienced.&#xD;<lb/>
They were ridiculed reprobated &amp; even slain&#xD;<lb/>
in the Cause of truth. Many have suffered&#xD;<lb/>
for asserting the roundness of the earth some&#xD;<lb/>
for asserting that the sun was fixed &amp; immovable&#xD;<lb/>
things of themselves of no consequence to Man&#xD;<lb/>
were Made by Despots articles of faith&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="30"
                xml:id="pb-30"
                facs="#i30"/>
            <lb/>
28&#xD;<lb/>
Credulity &amp; Prejudice the Grand&#xD;<lb/>
Obstacles to the general Hapiness of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Man</hi>
            <lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
Those People who have <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">least</del> most attended to the improvement&#xD;<lb/>
of the mind are generally <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">most</del> least prejudiced &amp;&#xD;<lb/>
Credulous. Nothing therefore so much tends&#xD;<lb/>
to the investigation of Truth as <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the improvement</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of the Mind</del>, as the Cultivation of Knowledge&#xD;<lb/>
This is very little regarded amongst&#xD;<lb/>
the generality of the people who are well&#xD;<lb/>
Pleased to take things as they find them&#xD;<lb/>
without searching into&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
