            <lb/>
1. Of the impossibility of the immaterial Human mind having&#xD;<lb/>
any intuitive ideas. 1. it is immutable by Hypothesis&#xD;<lb/>
but an immutable being is subject to no Change.&#xD;<lb/>
But that is not the same being which now reflects.&#xD;<lb/>
on A with that which reflects on B. –&#xD;<lb/>
but this <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">immutable</del> being by Hyp: sometimes&#xD;<lb/>
reflects on one <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp;</del> sometimes on another therefore&#xD;<lb/>
it changes. Ergo it is not immutable&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="56"
                xml:id="pb-56"
                facs="#i56"/>
            <lb/>
59&#xD;<lb/>
I woud argue from the following principles&#xD;<lb/>
1. That the Principle of Intelligence is similar in all organized&#xD;<lb/>
beings&#xD;<lb/>
2. That this principle is found always in perfection&#xD;<lb/>
in proportion as the organization&#xD;<lb/>
3. That they are always concomitant&#xD;<lb/>
4. That as the one decreases or increases so does&#xD;<lb/>
the other when the one ceases so does the other&#xD;<lb/>
5. That the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxxx</unclear>
            </del> I Power may cease with&#xD;<lb/>
out the Cessation of Organization proving&#xD;<lb/>
its Dependance upon it&#xD;<lb/>
