               <del rend="strikethrough">Chance.</del> – A Question is naturally sta<del rend="strikethrough">r</del>ted in every intelligent</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp; enquiring Mind what is the Ultimate End of our Existence</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The Solution of this Problem is of the Highest importance</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to Mankind. –</del>
            <lb/>
1. The Truth is eternal &amp; Unchangeable. The Defenders of&#xD;<lb/>
Immaterialism assert that their Opinions are fixed&#xD;<lb/>
on Her firm &amp; immutable Basis. Why then do they&#xD;<lb/>
fear &amp; investigation of their Hypothesis their&#xD;<lb/>
Sectaries are numerous &amp; powerful. We can never&#xD;<lb/>
overawe them. All known Truths are self evident.&#xD;<lb/>
demonstrable by self evident intermediate proofs&#xD;<lb/>
or founded on facts. On which of these is&#xD;<lb/>
Immaterialism founded. I beleive no one&#xD;<lb/>
will contend that it is an intuitive truth&#xD;<lb/>
unde from whence&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="62"
                xml:id="pb-62"
                facs="#i62"/>
            <lb/>
60&#xD;<lb/>
An Essay On the Ultimate End of Being&#xD;<lb/>
Man is a being Subject from the laws of his Constitution to pleasure&#xD;<lb/>
and pain. an instinctive Motive <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xx</unclear>
            </del> obliges him to fear&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; avoid the one &amp; to desire &amp; seek for the Other&#xD;<lb/>
This Capacity of seeking after Pleasure &amp; avoiding pain&#xD;<lb/>
is not confined to Man but is common to all&#xD;<lb/>
organized Beings &amp; is founded in the Natural&#xD;<lb/>
Aptitude of Things. We may then Lay it down&#xD;<lb/>
as a Grand Proposition that all organized beings&#xD;<lb/>
desire Happiness &amp; are averse to Misery&#xD;<lb/>
Allowing the Existence of a Supreme Intelligent&#xD;<lb/>
Being. We must at the same time suppose that&#xD;<lb/>
in forming organized Systems capable of P &amp; P&#xD;<lb/>
He must have had some end in View – &amp; this end&#xD;<lb/>
proceeding from the Will of a perfectly good <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">agent</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">must have been Good</del> (ie <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xx</unclear>
            </del> And powerful agent&#xD;<lb/>
must have been the best possible – But the best possible&#xD;<lb/>
End of being is happiness. The Proposition then is&#xD;<lb/>
Reduced to those several Cases.&#xD;<lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
Tenet 1st <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Being</del> The Ultimate End of Existence is Happiness&#xD;<lb/>
2 Man as an Organized <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">active intelligent</add> being coud not Exist without&#xD;<lb/>
the Sensations of Pleasure &amp; Pain. –&#xD;<lb/>
He coud not Exist without both&#xD;<lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
Man is fitted to arrive at &amp; enjoy the greatest&#xD;<lb/>
possible degree of Happiness by a proper Use of&#xD;<lb/>
His faculties&#xD;<lb/>
