69&#xD;<lb/>
– An Idyl –&#xD;<lb/>
Characters. Monobbon &amp; Trevelis.&#xD;<lb/>
L G Scene. Night Time&#xD;<lb/>
The Solar fire had just sunk in the bosom of the Western Ocean.&#xD;<lb/>
The trembling billows agitated by the gentle <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag51"
                ref="#misc_556"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag51">
          Zephyrs
        </term>
            </rs> glowed&#xD;<lb/>
with Rosy light: Trevelis hastened to the farthest point&#xD;<lb/>
of the Land. Where the last Rocks of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag52"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag52" type="place">
          cornwal
        </name>
            </rs>, elevated to&#xD;<lb/>
a Stupendous Height scorn the billows which idly&#xD;<lb/>
foam beneath them. No sound, no Voice was heard,&#xD;<lb/>
Save where the gentle breeze murmured in the Caverns&#xD;<lb/>
– of the Rocks, or the billows lashed the Shore –&#xD;<lb/>
Borne to the earth by Excessive fatigue, Despair &amp;&#xD;<lb/>
Misery seated in his haggard Countenance.&#xD;<lb/>
The unhappy Trevelis standing on a Rock. whose&#xD;<lb/>
Black brow oerhung the Waters. with a wild&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; confused Voice uttered the following Complaints&#xD;<lb/>
The Bowl of my Infelicity is not yet exausted, I have drained&#xD;<lb/>
the Cup to the bottom. I have drank the very dregs –&#xD;<lb/>
Yet still it is again presented full to my lips &amp; every&#xD;<lb/>
foll<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">n</hi> Draught is bitterer than the last – –&#xD;<lb/>
The last the most terrible of all, has overcome all my.&#xD;<lb/>
spirits. All Hopes are fled. except the last the most terrible&#xD;<lb/>
one, of enjoying peace in the calm &amp; placid arms&#xD;<lb/>
of Death. Come then thou art welcome to my embrace.&#xD;<lb/>
Thy grim Visage is no longer terrifying to me. Thy&#xD;<lb/>
Dart has been blunted &amp; corroded in the waters&#xD;<lb/>
of sorrow. O my Kalesa, my, Glory &amp; my Fame&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="72"
                xml:id="pb-72"
                facs="#i72"/>
            <lb/>
70&#xD;<lb/>
Ye are gone from me for ever. I shall see no&#xD;<lb/>
more that Charming Face. I shall hear no more&#xD;<lb/>
that sweet &amp; melodious Voice which like the&#xD;<lb/>
lyres of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag53"
                ref="#misc_011"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag53">
          the Muses
        </term>
            </rs> caused Happiness &amp; Joy to&#xD;<lb/>
sparkle in the Eyes of the attending Hearers.&#xD;<lb/>
As the Gaudy Visions of Happiness which transporting&#xD;<lb/>
the wrecth enslaved in a Dungeon, to Liberty&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Felicity, fly upon the approach <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>x</unclear>
            </del> of the&#xD;<lb/>
Morn<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">g</hi> &amp; leave him to torment<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">g</hi> cares &amp; dark&#xD;<lb/>
Despair. are ye Gone. But I will not long&#xD;<lb/>
endure this Excess of Misery. The Benificent Gods&#xD;<lb/>
have given me a power of terminating my&#xD;<lb/>
Existence when that Existence is too painful&#xD;<lb/>
to be endured –&#xD;<lb/>
He ended &amp; prepared to precipitate himself into&#xD;<lb/>
the foaming waves. When a Noise arresting him&#xD;<lb/>
from behind prevented his Destruction. <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">He turned</del>
            <lb/>
He turned his Head &amp; perceived the sage Druid&#xD;<lb/>
Mobodden. walking with hasty steps towards&#xD;<lb/>
him. <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">His</del> In his Countenance shone Venerable&#xD;<lb/>
Wisdom &amp; calm Resignation, His grey hairs&#xD;<lb/>
were dishevelled by the Wind. &amp; his silver&#xD;<lb/>
beard hung Uncultivated on his Manly Chest.&#xD;<lb/>
