106&#xD;<lb/>
3. We observe the difference in the Manners &amp; Climates of Nations&#xD;<lb/>
increase in proportion as the Similarity of the Climat decreases.&#xD;<lb/>
We cannot conceive two Climates more Different than those&#xD;<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag186"
                ref="#place_121"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag186" type="place">
          England
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag187"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag187" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs>. Nor two Nations more Unlike than the&#xD;<lb/>
English &amp; the Egyptians. In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag188"
                ref="#place_121"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag188" type="place">
          England
        </name>
            </rs> the Weather continually&#xD;<lb/>
varies from hot to Cold. from Wet to dry.&#xD;<lb/>
The Englisman constantly receiving new Sensations is&#xD;<lb/>
agitated like the Atmosphere in which He exists.&#xD;<lb/>
His Mind is almost constantly active. Torpor &amp; Lassitude&#xD;<lb/>
of the Mental Powers are to him rarely known –&#xD;<lb/>
He is brave, proud, honest &amp; hospitable. –&#xD;<lb/>
In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag189"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag189" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs> life is rather passive than active. nine months&#xD;<lb/>
in the Year the Body is oppressed by heat. &amp; the Soul in a&#xD;<lb/>
State of Apathy. The Egyptian far from being tormented by&#xD;<lb/>
a restless curiosity sighs after Calm Tranquillity.&#xD;<lb/>
Repose to him is enjoyment &amp; the sofa of Course the most&#xD;<lb/>
luxurious piece of furniture in his Apartment. –&#xD;<lb/>
Constantly feeling the same Heat &amp; the Same Sensation&#xD;<lb/>
Two thirds of the year He is idle patient &amp; Grave. –&#xD;<lb/>
The European pleasures &amp; Occupations are totally unknown&#xD;<lb/>
to him. –&#xD;<lb/>
A Monotony which woud be Death to the European is the&#xD;<lb/>
greatest Felicity of the Egyptian. –&#xD;<lb/>
Nor is it to be supposed that Turkish Despotism has destroyed&#xD;<lb/>
the Energies of the Mind in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag190"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag190" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs>. &amp; that it is from moral&#xD;<lb/>
Causes that the English are so much superior to the&#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Egyptians parallels may be drawn between <rs xml:id="ttag191" ref="#place_475" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag191" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
               </rs> &amp; <rs xml:id="ttag192" ref="#place_897" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag192" type="place">
          France
        </name>
               </rs>
            </del>
            <lb/>
The same Comparison might have been drawn between&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag193"
                ref="#place_897"
