                facs="#i109"/>
            <lb/>
107&#xD;<lb/>
And if the Air &amp; Climate give<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">s</del> a peculiar Stamp to the Character&#xD;<lb/>
of an Individuals – Any No of persons under a Similar&#xD;<lb/>
Climate &amp; atmosphere. will have a Certain Similarity&#xD;<lb/>
in their General Manners &amp; Character. which tho’&#xD;<lb/>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">entirely destroyed by</add> Moral Causes &amp;c <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">may entirely destroy in</del> some Individuals&#xD;<lb/>
will nevertheless prevail amongst the Generality of&#xD;<lb/>
2 The Variation of the Atmosphere the different degrees of heat&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Cold to which Man is Exposed in every Country have a very&#xD;<lb/>
great Effect on the Mind. In fine weather when the Sun&#xD;<lb/>
Shines bright &amp; the pure air is warmed by the gentle Zephyr.&#xD;<lb/>
Cheerfulness Gaiety &amp; a love of Action prevail in the Mind.&#xD;<lb/>
On the Contrary when the Sun is hid from our view by the Black&#xD;<lb/>
            <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">NE</unclear>. When the air is cold &amp; the Sky oppressed by Clouds.&#xD;<lb/>
The Mind is Dull Cheerless &amp; Melancholy. –&#xD;<lb/>
In the Intense Heats of Summer indolence is far more prevalent&#xD;<lb/>
in every Nation than in the Spring –&#xD;<lb/>
If a transition from temperate to Cold from fine <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">clear</add> to dull&#xD;<lb/>
Weather so materially affects the Manners &amp; Characters&#xD;<lb/>
of the Same Person. The Constant presence of the same&#xD;<lb/>
Sensations. woud uniformly produce the same temper of&#xD;<lb/>
Mind as a short continuance of them. –&#xD;<lb/>
So that the Englisman (whom <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the temporary Existence of</add> Dull &amp; cold weather made&#xD;<lb/>
melancholy &amp; dejected. <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">for a time</add> if transported to a Clime where the&#xD;<lb/>
Weather was always cold. &amp; the Sky clouded wou’d be&#xD;<lb/>
always dull melancholy &amp; phlegmatic –&#xD;<lb/>
If the temper &amp; Manners of most individuals are so affected by&#xD;<lb/>
the Weather. The Manners &amp; Character of <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">No individuals</del>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">under</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">any No of people in</add>
            <lb/>
the same Climat must from the Similarity of the Weather&#xD;<lb/>
be in some respect similar. –&#xD;<lb/>
must from the Uniformity of Sensation be likewise similar&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="110"
                xml:id="pb-110"
                facs="#i110"/>
            <lb/>
108&#xD;<lb/>
– The Influence of Climat on National Manners &amp; Character –&#xD;<lb/>
A Peculiarity of Manners &amp; Character distinguishes every Nation.&#xD;<lb/>
And tho’ many Individuals may entirely differ from these general&#xD;<lb/>
Characteristics, yet the Inhabitants of every Climat taken collectively&#xD;<lb/>
are tinged with a peculiar Set of Manners &amp; distinguished from&#xD;<lb/>
other Nations by some general Character. –&#xD;<lb/>
The Pride of the Englishman &amp; the Levity of the French are alike&#xD;<lb/>
proverbial; tho’ there are many humble Characters in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag195"
                ref="#place_121"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag195" type="place">
          England
        </name>
            </rs>;&#xD;<lb/>
as well as serious men in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag196"
                ref="#place_897"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag196" type="place">
          France
        </name>
            </rs> . –&#xD;<lb/>
There are two kinds of Causes which may be supposed to influence&#xD;<lb/>
the Genius &amp; Manners of Nations, ie Moral &amp; Natural ones.&#xD;<lb/>
* by Moral Causes may be understood. the Nature of the political&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Ecclesiastical Government. the Modes of Education. The&#xD;<lb/>
Wants of the People &amp; its Relation towards other states.&#xD;<lb/>
by Natural Ones. the Nature of the Climat. the Qualities of the&#xD;<lb/>
Atmosphere &amp;c. –&#xD;<lb/>
* <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Some philosophers have attempted to account for all National</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">difference from Moral Causes entirely disregarding physical causes</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">That Moral Causes have by far <add>the</add> greatest effect on the Mind of <unclear>Man</unclear>
            </del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">must be acknowledged must be acknowledged by every</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">one acquainted with ancient &amp; modern History.</del>
            <lb/>
At present we shall confine our attention to the Consideration of Natural&#xD;<lb/>
causes. whose Influence on the Human mind may be inferred&#xD;<lb/>
from the following Reasons –&#xD;<lb/>
1<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">st</hi>. The Character of every Individual is a Collection of his Qualities&#xD;<lb/>
which are his Virtues, <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">his</del> Vices, <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">his</del> Manners, Customs &amp;c –&#xD;<lb/>
These it is plain, are formed by his sensations, Affections&#xD;<lb/>
&amp; Wants. Whatever then tends to Influence his Sensations,&#xD;<lb/>
affections &amp; Wants must tend to Influence his Character –&#xD;<lb/>
But these are Materially influenced by Physical Causes –&#xD;<lb/>
Therefore his Manners &amp; Character are influenced by&#xD;<lb/>
Physical Causes –&#xD;<lb/>
* <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag197"
                ref="#person_080"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag197" type="person">
          Hume
        </name>
            </rs> –&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="111"
                xml:id="pb-111"
                facs="#i111"/>
            <lb/>
109&#xD;<lb/>
* Was it not <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">liberal</del> Science which laid the&#xD;<lb/>
foundations for Ecclesiastical Liberty in&#xD;<lb/>
Europe: &amp; <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which opened the Eyes of all Europe</del>
            <lb/>
The learning of Luther &amp; the Zeal of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag198"
                ref="#person_759"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag198" type="person">
          Calvin
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
had little availed if Men had not been&#xD;<lb/>
more enligtned in the Age in which&#xD;<lb/>
they appeared than in the preceding one,&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag199"
